body: Arc seems determined to add time at home to the cycling time, so it didn’t
Picked up the green screen. It came in a huge Amazon box
It was a great morning to ride the scooter to work. There were very few clouds in the sky and the temperature was mild. I hit 40kph along the Greenslopes section of the Veloway.
I had to come back to the hospital to help Emma. A Hi-Flow research patient turned up this evening!
Forester 239294 kms, 30.36L of Vortex 98 at $1.679/L

Instead of heading down the road past the school, I went straight ahead and ended up in Belmont. Unfortunately there was no footpath at all this way, and I had to use the side of the road! Yikes. Next time I will turn left at the golf course abs go back that way.

Had dinner at the club. On Sunday the special is Roast. Anita had the silverside and I picked the lamb as usual. We then checked out the poker machines. Anita lost $50 and I won $35, which covered the dinner and drinks.
I redesigned the light bar to fit on the scooter. I printed a quick prototype version to see if I got the measurements right. It was almost finished by the time we got back from the club!
We just got home and Katherine wanted shaker fries from McDonalds. Since we didn’t have coffee at the club, I ordered coffee at McDonald’s.
The light bar fits and seems good enough to use for a while. The lugs have not broken off yet.
They are widening the road for a new housing development, so one lane is closed.
Had to use the toilet in a hurry! Good thing it was open and not being used. The combinations pumpkin soup this morning and the club meal last night and the evening coffee.

I was looking for a better footpath to use this morning and tried to get to Lumley Street. Next time I should go to the usual intersection on Dawson Road, and then turn down Cale Street at the top of the hill. The path past the shops on the backstreet is generally smoother than the one on the main road.
Arc failed early in the afternoon! ...and didn’t restart until I was nearly home.
It had been raining this afternoon, so I was worried I wouldn’t be able to ride home for a while.
Arc crashed as we stopped to wait for the the road works! But it probably did take 20 minutes longer than usual to do the school trip.
The Rentokill man came to inspect the white ant traps. He found some activity in trap #9 near the rubbish bins.

Drove to work in the WRX. There was a storm passing over the Southside as I was leaving. There was a lot of water running down the gutters in the street. I even heard some thunder. It had barely rained in the city.

Big Arc fail Thursday. I think I put the iPhone on the charger at work which may have been the cause? Anyway it missed the trip home via Jake’s house. I also took the Salisbury route in the WRX so it would have taken longer I suppose.
Arcare failed again today. It’s almost the same as yesterday.
Updating iOS took longer than I planned so it was still installing as we left and it wasn’t until we were halfway to the old museum that it was ready.
I finally found a place where I could buy some 303 Aerospace Protectant. It’s supposed to be better than Armoural. It’s expensive though at $28!

They also had a great range of LED headlights. I took a picture of the unit out of the box which I will use to see what I need to change to get the light fitted. I may have to leave the rubber boot off? There might be an opportunity here to 3D print a special boot for it.
I parked near the bridge. It was a good well lit location when retuning at night.
It was a great afternoon to get out. The temperature was perfect. I arrived in the CBD just on sunset so I was able to get some great photos around the river.
Back at the car. A good spot for the base.
Forester 239568 kms, 33.87L of Vortex 98 at $1.509/L
The valve cap on the front wheel of the Zero 9 broke today, so I found a model on Thingiverse and made some new ones in red.
Scored a parking spot on the bottom floor for the LEAF.
The battery temperature had dropped to 26°C - down from 29°C while parked on this cooler day.
Stayed home to work on Tuesday. Got a lot of the storybook completed. Looking into digital flip books.
Incremental increase in the internal diameter of the valve cap design to adjust for inaccurate plastic printing. Internal holes tend to be smaller than drawn.
The road works deviation is creating a huge pothole.
I bought the bacon and egg McMuffin meal deal. I hope this doesn’t set me back on my weight reduction plans! I will have to be careful with this evenings UberEats dinner.
Dramas this morning with Rachael from Ruby Blue casting agency needing photos and details at very short notice.
I had an idea to make a 3D printed plug for the cable ports to the sleep rooms. They are currently stuffing rolled up pyjamas in the holes.

The in-patient ward is closing and we will be back to full sleep lab service as of next Monday.

I unpacked the stored equipment and put it back In the rooms. Full testing required on Monday.

Went to Arcare to get Mum’s Medicare number. Eventually found it in her hearing aid bag.

Handed in the permission for the COVID vaccination on the 30th March.
Anita was hungry so we had lunch at the Shingle Inn. We both had the Classic Omelette. I’ve eaten too much already.
I bought a cheap small wallet / credit card holder because the one I bought in Japan had broken from holding too many cards.
We also went to Rebel Sport next door for Anita to buy some had weights (2kg) and a blue pool noodle for her exercise program.
The valve on the rear wheel of the scooter is really close to the motor, so I had to print a thinner valve cap to fit it. The cap wall was too thin to print the knurling. Something had to give!
Went to Autobarn to buy some new windscreen wipers for the Forester. The Wipertech ones I have on the shelf are for the WRX.
Anita bought a flower arrangement for her mother.
Andrew was after a heat gun. I thought he wanted a proper one, but he really wanted a butane torch. We have one at work.
We drive to Mudite’s place to drop off the flowers. They weren’t there so Anita put them under the house. It was raining.
I parked the LEAF around the side of the old museum and waited for Katherine’s bus to return from QYO camp at Mt Tamborine. The LEAF used about 2-3% SOC running the air con
Katherine’s bus arrived and we went out to get her. It was raining even more.
Had to park on the roof. I parked next to a Tesla M3 again. Took a shortcut down the nearby stairs to level 4. It’s probably the best way back again if it’s raining.
Forester 239823 kms, 33.96L of Vortex 98 at $1.509/L

It rained all night. I left the dehumidifier running all night and I’ve been able to completely refill all the water containers I use for ironing. The humidity in the office has been up in the 70-80% range for the last few days!
Arc was off until I relaunched it on the way back.
There was heavy traffic for the trip home. As usual the LEAF is the best place to be in this sort of traffic.
Made my own breakfast this morning.
I will have to take not of the actual start and finish times because I don’t think the trip takes this long? This probably includes the carpark time getting ready to leave etc.
Bought a bacon and egg McMuffin on the way home. The traffic looked terrible on the way to school but had cleared a fair bit by then.
They are working on the weekend and blocking a lane.
Dropped Katherine off at the school for her musical practice.
The LED light in the bedroom has failed so I bought some more. These lights are supposed to last several years. So far that hasn’t been the case!
Bought some sausage sizzles for lunch. Anita already had lunch and said she would eat half, but had the whole thing anyway. They were a bit burnt.

Waiting to pick up Katherine. I didn’t charge the leaf last night and the painter was using the power point so I haven’t charged it today. I left home with 35%, so I’m estimating that we will get back with around 20% SOC.
Dropping off Katherine at the QYO for the concert this afternoon. Anita can be in the limited audience, so I will watch the live stream from somewhere nearby.
There was an hour to kill before the concert starts at 1:30pm, so Anita wanted to get some coffee at McDonalds.
We came down to the nearby park to chill. There was a lady sitting on the fence nearby complaining about someone. You could hear here from the other side of the carpark.
We drove further along and parked again. I played a quick game of Pokémon Go.
Anita needed to go to the toilet.
I dropped off Anita and then parked up the road in the usual spot to watch the concert on their livestream.
It was a short but well played concert! I was able to turn up the stereo in the car to listen.
The lane was blocked again, so we had to wait for the other cars.
Forester 240113 kms,  36.89L of Vortex 98 at $1.889/L
